notes:
ID confirmed by Suvdtsetseg Chuluunbat. The sequence is closer to C fulva from Mongolia than to other C annulicornis from North America. This is likely a result of the vicariant speciation.-Xin Zhou

ID confirmed by Morse: "This specimen appears to be typical Ceraclea (Athripsodina) annulicornis (Stephens, 1836). This species is known from throughout the Holarctic Region. Ceraclea annulicornis is very different from C. (C.) fulva (Rambur, 1842), a European sponge-feeding species in a different subgenus. If the molecular data are suggesting that there are additional haplotypes of C. annulicornis, then this matter needs more-detailed review of C. annulicornis from throughout its range."-John Morse, Apr 19, 2010.

notes: "(ID-03502 to 03508) This is Ceraclea excise (Morton, 1904). In 1975 (p. 42), I synonymized with C. excise the following 3 subspecies/species: Athripsodes perplexus nordus Milne, 1934; Athripsodes miscus Ross, 1941; and Athripsodes scopulosus Leonard & Leonard, 1949. Currently, as seen in the Trichoptera World Checklist, Ceraclea misca (Ross, 1941) is considered to be the valid name of the North American species, even though C. p. norda has priority. (This taxonomic problem needs to be corrected.) The males of C. excisa (Morton, 1904) and C. misca are very similar, but the females, larvae, and pupae are different. It would be interesting to get some COI sequences from specimens from Alaska (the C. p. norda type locality), Wisconsin/Minnesota (the C. misca type localities), and Michigan (the C. scopulosa type locality) to discover how many haplotypes of this species occur in North America. In any case, Suvdaa's identification is correct according to current understanding: the Palearctic C. excisa is almost certainly different from the one or more species that occur in North America."-John Morse, Apr 19, 2010.

notes: "(ID-03502 to 03508) This is Ceraclea excise (Morton, 1904). In 1975 (p. 42), I synonymized with C. excise the following 3 subspecies/species: Athripsodes perplexus nordus Milne, 1934; Athripsodes miscus Ross, 1941; and Athripsodes scopulosus Leonard & Leonard, 1949. Currently, as seen in the Trichoptera World Checklist, Ceraclea misca (Ross, 1941) is considered to be the valid name of the North American species, even though C. p. norda has priority. (This taxonomic problem needs to be corrected.) The males of C. excisa (Morton, 1904) and C. misca are very similar, but the females, larvae, and pupae are different. It would be interesting to get some COI sequences from specimens from Alaska (the C. p. norda type locality), Wisconsin/Minnesota (the C. misca type localities), and Michigan (the C. scopulosa type locality) to discover how many haplotypes of this species occur in North America. In any case, Suvdaa's identification is correct according to current understanding: the Palearctic C. excisa is almost certainly different from the one or more species that occur in North America."-John Morse, Apr 19, 2010.

notes: "(ID-03502 to 03508) This is Ceraclea excise (Morton, 1904). In 1975 (p. 42), I synonymized with C. excise the following 3 subspecies/species: Athripsodes perplexus nordus Milne, 1934; Athripsodes miscus Ross, 1941; and Athripsodes scopulosus Leonard & Leonard, 1949. Currently, as seen in the Trichoptera World Checklist, Ceraclea misca (Ross, 1941) is considered to be the valid name of the North American species, even though C. p. norda has priority. (This taxonomic problem needs to be corrected.) The males of C. excisa (Morton, 1904) and C. misca are very similar, but the females, larvae, and pupae are different. It would be interesting to get some COI sequences from specimens from Alaska (the C. p. norda type locality), Wisconsin/Minnesota (the C. misca type localities), and Michigan (the C. scopulosa type locality) to discover how many haplotypes of this species occur in North America. In any case, Suvdaa's identification is correct according to current understanding: the Palearctic C. excisa is almost certainly different from the one or more species that occur in North America."-John Morse, Apr 19, 2010.

notes: "(ID-03502 to 03508) This is Ceraclea excise (Morton, 1904). In 1975 (p. 42), I synonymized with C. excise the following 3 subspecies/species: Athripsodes perplexus nordus Milne, 1934; Athripsodes miscus Ross, 1941; and Athripsodes scopulosus Leonard & Leonard, 1949. Currently, as seen in the Trichoptera World Checklist, Ceraclea misca (Ross, 1941) is considered to be the valid name of the North American species, even though C. p. norda has priority. (This taxonomic problem needs to be corrected.) The males of C. excisa (Morton, 1904) and C. misca are very similar, but the females, larvae, and pupae are different. It would be interesting to get some COI sequences from specimens from Alaska (the C. p. norda type locality), Wisconsin/Minnesota (the C. misca type localities), and Michigan (the C. scopulosa type locality) to discover how many haplotypes of this species occur in North America. In any case, Suvdaa's identification is correct according to current understanding: the Palearctic C. excisa is almost certainly different from the one or more species that occur in North America."-John Morse, Apr 19, 2010.

notes: "(ID-03502 to 03508) This is Ceraclea excise (Morton, 1904). In 1975 (p. 42), I synonymized with C. excise the following 3 subspecies/species: Athripsodes perplexus nordus Milne, 1934; Athripsodes miscus Ross, 1941; and Athripsodes scopulosus Leonard & Leonard, 1949. Currently, as seen in the Trichoptera World Checklist, Ceraclea misca (Ross, 1941) is considered to be the valid name of the North American species, even though C. p. norda has priority. (This taxonomic problem needs to be corrected.) The males of C. excisa (Morton, 1904) and C. misca are very similar, but the females, larvae, and pupae are different. It would be interesting to get some COI sequences from specimens from Alaska (the C. p. norda type locality), Wisconsin/Minnesota (the C. misca type localities), and Michigan (the C. scopulosa type locality) to discover how many haplotypes of this species occur in North America. In any case, Suvdaa's identification is correct according to current understanding: the Palearctic C. excisa is almost certainly different from the one or more species that occur in North America."-John Morse, Apr 19, 2010.

notes: "(ID-03502 to 03508) This is Ceraclea excise (Morton, 1904). In 1975 (p. 42), I synonymized with C. excise the following 3 subspecies/species: Athripsodes perplexus nordus Milne, 1934; Athripsodes miscus Ross, 1941; and Athripsodes scopulosus Leonard & Leonard, 1949. Currently, as seen in the Trichoptera World Checklist, Ceraclea misca (Ross, 1941) is considered to be the valid name of the North American species, even though C. p. norda has priority. (This taxonomic problem needs to be corrected.) The males of C. excisa (Morton, 1904) and C. misca are very similar, but the females, larvae, and pupae are different. It would be interesting to get some COI sequences from specimens from Alaska (the C. p. norda type locality), Wisconsin/Minnesota (the C. misca type localities), and Michigan (the C. scopulosa type locality) to discover how many haplotypes of this species occur in North America. In any case, Suvdaa's identification is correct according to current understanding: the Palearctic C. excisa is almost certainly different from the one or more species that occur in North America."-John Morse, Apr 19, 2010.
